## 3. The Three Pillars of the Architecture

To implement this theoretical framework, three distinct structural layers must cooperate:

### A. Volumetric Phase Gating (Neuro-Attention)
In a 170-billion-node design scale, calculating global interactions would be computationally prohibitive. The architecture uses a spatial attention filter that projects a 3D Gaussian envelope over the lattice. Nodes outside this focus envelope are dynamically decoupled ($K \to 0$), isolating noise and focusing energy density purely on active regions.

### B. Thermodynamic Value Modulation (Neuro-Valence)
Rather than optimizing for an external mathematical loss function, the system is modulated by local entropy changes. Using the Helmholtz free energy equation, the system evaluates:

$$V(t) = -\frac{d}{dt} \left( E_{local} - T \cdot S_{local} \right)$$

States of decreasing entropy (positive valence) are reinforced, while high-entropy states trigger virtual temperature ($T$) spikes, injecting phase noise to stimulate exploration of new attractor states.

### C. Tripartite Cellular Scaling (Neuro-Anatomy)
A key distinction of this framework is the inclusion of non-neuronal cells. By maintaining biological scaling ratios (86B Neurons to 40B Astrocytes), the architecture splits processing tasks:
*   **Neurons** handle high-frequency signal propagation and phase-locking.
*   **Astrocytes** act as slow-wave calcium networks ($0.1 - 0.5\text{ Hz}$), dynamically adjusting the coupling strengths ($K$) of the faster networks to maintain systemic metastability.

